  "prompt": "What are the books that should be read by everyone?",
  "response": "There are many books universally praised for their themes, literary quality, and impact on culture. Here are some that are often recommended for everyone to read:\n\n1. **To Kill a Mockingbird by Harper Lee** - A profound novel addressing racial injustice and moral growth in the American South.\n\n2. **1984 by George Orwell** - A dystopian tale exploring themes of government surveillance and totalitarianism.\n\n3. **Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen** - A classic romance novel that also critiques the British class system.\n\n4. **The Great Gatsby by F. Scott Fitzgerald** - An exploration of the American Dream and the decadence of the Jazz Age.\n\n5. **Moby-Dick by Herman Melville** - An epic tale of obsession and the human condition.\n\n6. **War and Peace by Leo Tolstoy** - A magnum opus that delves into Russian society, history, and philosophy.\n\n7. **Crime and Punishment by Fyodor Dostoevsky** - A gripping psychological novel about guilt, redemption, and moral dilemmas.\n\n8. **One Hundred Years of Solitude by Gabriel Garcia Marquez** - A richly woven tale of magical realism set within a mythical Latin American town.\n\n9. **Brave New World by Aldous Huxley** - A prophetic novel about the dangers of dehumanizing technologies and societal control.\n\n10. **The Catcher in the Rye by J.D. Salinger** - A nuanced portrayal of teenage angst and existential questioning.\n\n11. **The Lord of the Rings by J.R.R. Tolkien** - A timeless fantasy epic exploring themes of power, friendship, and sacrifice.\n\n12. **Meditations by Marcus Aurelius** - Insights from a Roman Emperor promoting Stoic philosophy and personal conduct.\n\n13. **Invisible Man by Ralph Ellison** - An intense exploration of racial discrimination and identity in America.\n\n14. **Beloved by Toni Morrison** - A haunting and powerful narrative dealing with the legacy of slavery.\n\n15. **Sapiens: A Brief History of Humankind by Yuval Noah Harari** - An engaging overview of human history, offering provocative insights into our species.\n\nThese titles span various genres and time periods, offering diverse perspectives and themes that can enrich one's understanding of the world and the human experience.",
